04:43.000 --> 04:56.000
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, the past weekend Washington has produced several developments of great interest to our state.

04:56.000 --> 05:09.000
I'm very happy to be able to report that the Atomic Energy Commission has announced that it will go ahead with a $30 million gas-cool reactor to produce electric power from atomic energy.

05:09.000 --> 05:15.000
The AEC announced that this project will be located at Oak Ridge or two primary reasons.

05:15.000 --> 05:29.000
First Oak Ridge offers the operational advantage of the Oak Ridge National Laboratory, where the AEC's primary research and development efforts in the gas-cool reactor field have been carried on and will continue.

05:30.000 --> 05:41.000
Second Oak Ridge provides an area where the 25,000 kilowatts this reactor will absorb, will produce, can be absorbed and in the TBA system.

05:41.000 --> 05:51.000
Incidentally, this recommendation for a gas-cool reactor was made by the TBA some six or seven years ago, and I'm glad it's now a reality.

05:51.000 --> 05:58.000
This decision of the government to go ahead and develop a gas-cool reactor power plant is most welcome.

05:58.000 --> 06:04.000
It has moved the problem of developing atomic plants for electrical power off-dead centers.

06:04.000 --> 06:12.000
Private enterprise will continue to be assisted by the government in this field, but this first step of the government will get the ball rolling.

06:12.000 --> 06:23.000
It is more significant that our government has made this decision, because the British and the Russians have been far ahead of the United States and the gas-cool reactor field.

06:23.000 --> 06:35.000
Whoever works out the gas-cool reactor first in the right sort of way and in the successful way will decide who will be the first to make atomic power economically competitive.

06:36.000 --> 06:41.000
And Senator Albert Gore has been working effectively and bringing about this important step.

06:41.000 --> 06:48.000
We're all delighted that the AEC decided our Oak Ridge people are to be the ones to handle this new plant.

06:48.000 --> 07:03.000
Turning now from atomic energy to another subject of importance to Tennessee, I'm glad to be able to report that the Cotton Acryg rental bill, S-1455, passed the Senate by a voice vote this week.

07:03.000 --> 07:15.000
This bill is a great importance to the small cotton farmers in the entire southeast area and of equal importance to the small business man, such as the Genre and the Cotton Seed Oil Mill operator.

07:15.000 --> 07:28.000
The bill will permit a cotton farmer to rent all or part of his Cotton Acryg allotment to another producer within certain limitations, so as not to increase the overall national Cotton Acryg allotment.

07:29.000 --> 07:41.000
It will apply to the crop years of 1959, 60 and 61. The agreements run for one year but are renewable and do not affect the allotment of the farmer who rents the AEC Ridge.

07:41.000 --> 07:51.000
I think the arrangement will help a lot of small farmers stay in business who would otherwise be forced to abandon their farms and seek work in the cities.

07:51.000 --> 08:02.000
The foundation of our economy in my mind is built upon the small, family-sized farmer. This is another step to help him continue to make a decent living.

08:02.000 --> 08:13.000
I might mention in closing that hearings will resume this past week on the bill which would take the big automobile manufacturers out of the finance business.

08:13.000 --> 08:28.000
Senator Manroni and I have introduced bills on this subject. The object of these bills is to offer some protection from monopolistic big business to the small finance companies and banks and try to keep some of the money at home.

08:28.000 --> 08:42.000
If the big auto industries take over the financing business entirely, the eventual result would be higher interest rates for every automobile buyer, dealers and hundreds of small banks and finance firms

08:42.000 --> 08:54.000
would eventually be put out of business. Last week on this program I of course, you met Beverly Baker who was our Tennessee cherry blossom princess.

08:54.000 --> 09:10.000
I think she was the most beautiful princess of all but they chose the queen by turn of the wheel. Unfortunately, Miss Baker was not selected. It went to a very lovely girl, Miss Harris who is the daughter of Congressman Harris of Arkansas.

09:10.000 --> 09:17.000
That's about all the time I have for the program on this occasion so thank you and goodbye until next week.

09:17.000 --> 09:41.000
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, one of the most heated debates of this session of Congress has been in progress on the Senate floor for more than a week now.

09:42.000 --> 09:52.000
The subject is the Kennedy Urban Labor Bill and amendments offered to that bill. Almost an entire day it was taken up as debate on the so-called Bill of Rights Amendment.

09:52.000 --> 10:02.000
This was offered by Senator Matheu and of Arkansas whose fine work in exposing corruption and wrongdoing in some labor unions has been most commendable.

10:03.000 --> 10:25.000
When this amendment came to a vote, I joined 44 other senators in voting against it. Among those voting with me against the amendment where senators go or Senator Long and Eleanor of Louisiana, Senator Olen Johnson of South Carolina, Senators Johnson and Yarborough of Texas, and Senators Hill and Sparkman of Alabama.

10:25.000 --> 10:33.000
The vote was a tie of 45 to 45. Vice President Nixon broke the tie by voting for the amendment and it carried.

10:33.000 --> 10:43.000
At first last, glad Senator Matheu and his amendment appears to accomplish just what its title suggests, a bill of rights for our union members.

10:43.000 --> 10:54.000
After I had read carefully the full implications behind the amendment, I decided to vote against it. Section 103 of the amendment I believe was the most dangerous part.

10:54.000 --> 11:06.000
In brief, it would authorize the Attorney General of the United States to bring in injunctive actions against any labor organization or any member or officer thereof in any state.

11:06.000 --> 11:14.000
And this includes our own state of Tennessee, with no protection of jury trial provided for the rights of any person or group accused.

11:14.000 --> 11:28.000
This is the very thing that we insisted upon in the civil rights arguments last year. That a jury trial is essential protection that must be offered in any citizen or group who is accused, whatever the charges.

11:28.000 --> 11:36.000
No one can say to what extent federal intervention into state affairs would be carried under this section of the material amendment.

11:36.000 --> 11:46.000
A study of the Kennedy Irvin bill, S155, I feel certain that the rights of union members are provided for most adequately.

11:46.000 --> 12:00.000
Another aspect of the material amendment which I feel contains dangerous implications is the section making union membership list available to candidates for office and union elections, whether they are bona fide or candidates or not.

12:00.000 --> 12:07.000
This opens each individual union membership list up to a wide variety of pressure and even intimidation.

12:07.000 --> 12:15.000
Communists could use the list for infiltration. Phony candidates could use the list for any illicit pressure they wished.

12:15.000 --> 12:24.000
The Kennedy bill provides avenues for bona fide candidates to present their campaign literature without making the membership list public.

12:25.000 --> 12:43.000
I think this is much fair and safer. The closest of the vote on the material amendment and the heat of the debate on every stage of this labor legislation is a good indication of concern on the part of every senator that we produce fair legislation to labor and to management.

12:44.000 --> 12:58.000
And it indicates concern that we provide the means to curb corruption and wrong, where it exists in the union movement without doing damage to the overwhelming majority of honest and democratically run unions.

12:58.000 --> 13:06.000
And then also ladies and gentlemen this week another matter of importance happened form the viewpoint of the people of Tennessee.

13:06.000 --> 13:19.000
That was the unexpected nomination by President Eisenhower, a former congressman Brooks Hayes to serve the one and one half years left in Dr. Welch's term on the Tennessee Valley Authority.

13:19.000 --> 13:31.000
I've known congressman Hayes for many years as a member of the House of Representatives. I know that he is an honest, sincere, good man and will try to do a good public duty.

13:31.000 --> 13:44.000
I of course do not want the TVA to get mixed up into politics. And I would want to question congressman Hayes about his vote for the so-called Dixon Yates deal.

13:44.000 --> 13:53.000
But in general I have confidence in congressman Hayes and I know if he says that he will try his very best for the TVA that he will do so.

